<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,258,1111]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,726,751]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[324,400,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Peckia</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[409,547,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
(
<emphasis box="[418,437,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[457,547,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[761,886,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[761,782,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[800,818,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[838,886,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, since them both have gena and parafacial with gray microtrichosity; males have vesica with a rounded lobe proximally and apex hook-shaped, and females have T5 with a triangular posterior margin. In addition, these species are both associated to coastal environments. However, males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[374,542,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[374,393,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[413,432,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[452,542,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from those of 
<taxonomicName box="[784,910,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[784,803,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[823,841,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[861,910,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having juxtal lateral plate square and short (shorter than length of phallic tube), as opposed to pointed and longer than length of phallic tube (
<figureCitation box="[1240,1323,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1673,1696]" captionTargetBox="[266,1299,222,1587]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[261,1326,193,1655]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–20. Male terminalia of Peckia spp. 11–12. Peckia (Euboettcheria) collusor (Curran &amp; Walley), specimen from Pará, Jari (MPEG). 11. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus in left lateral view; arrow points to preapical projection with tuft of setulae. 12. Cerci in dorsal view; arrow points to preapical projection with tuft of setulae. 13–14. Peckia (Euboettcheria) epimelia (Lopes), specimen from Pará, Jari (MPEG). 13. Epandrium, surstylus and cercus in left lateral view; arrow points to flat apical projection. 14. Cerci in dorsal view; arrow points to elongated basal projection with spines and setulae. 15. Peckia (Euboettcheria) tridentata (Hall), specimen from Pará, Jari (MPEG); epandrium, surstylus and cercus in left lateral view; arrow points to apical spines. 16. Peckia (Peckia) hillifera (Aldrich), specimen from Pará, Bragança (MPEG); distiphallus in left lateral view. 17. Peckia (Peckia) lutzi (Lopes), specimen from Pará, Bragança (MPEG); distiphallus in left lateral view. 18. Peckia (Peckia) uncinata (Hall), specimen from Pará, Serra Norte (MPEG); genital segments, cercus and surstylus in left lateral view. 19. Peckia (Peckia) pexata (Wulp), specimen from Pará, Jari (MPEG); cercus in left lateral view; arrow points to rounded projection. 20. Peckia (Peckia) chrysostoma (Wiedemann), specimen from Pará, Belém (MPEG); epandrium, surstylus and cercus in left lateral view. Scales bars = 0.5 mm. Abbreviation: jp = juxtal lateral plate." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456124/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Females of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[183,352,906,931]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[183,202,908,931]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[223,237,908,931]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[262,352,906,931]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have ST8 wider than long and spiracle 6 located on the intersegmentary membrane (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1422,906,931]" captionStart="FIGURES 81–86" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1911,1934]" captionTargetBox="[176,1406,197,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[173,1406,193,1888]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 81–86. Peckia (Peckia) hillifera (Aldrich), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 81. Abdominal sternites and tergite 6 in ventral view. 82. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 83. Spermatheca in lateral view. 84. Abdomen in posterior view. 85. Abdomen in dorsal view. 86. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 79, 83–84 = 2 mm; 80 = 0.5 mm; 81 = 0.1 mm; 82 = 1 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456147/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName box="[249,371,942,967]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[249,268,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[285,299,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[323,371,942,967]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ST7 and ST8 are fused and spiracle 6 is located on T6 (
<figureCitation box="[999,1083,942,967]" captionStart="FIGURES 87–92" captionStartId="25.[151,264,1905,1928]" captionTargetBox="[173,1435,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1435,193,1885]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 87–92. Peckia (Peckia) lutzi (Lopes), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 87. Abdominal sternites and tergite 6 in ventral view. 88. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 89. Spermatheca in apical view. 90. Abdomen in posterior view. 91. Abdomen in dorsal view. 92. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 85, 88–90 = 2 mm; 86–87 = 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456149/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 87</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,258,1111]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis box="[199,275,978,1003]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Peckia</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[282,418,978,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
(
<emphasis box="[291,310,980,1003]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[328,418,978,1003]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[697,803,978,1003]" name="Bahamas" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Bahamas</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[814,876,978,1003]" name="Cuba" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Cuba</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[887,980,978,1003]" name="Jamaica" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[991,1080,978,1003]" name="Mexico" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<collectingRegion box="[991,1080,978,1003]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Mexico</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1091,1183,979,1002]" name="Panama" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<collectingRegion box="[1091,1183,979,1002]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Panama</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1194,1330,978,1003]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Trinidad &amp; 
<collectingRegion box="[179,265,1014,1039]" country="Trinidad and Tobago" name="Tobago" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Tobago</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[276,391,1014,1039]" name="Venezuela" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[486,545,1015,1039]" name="United States of America" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">USA</collectingCountry>
, and the above records are the first for 
<collectingCountry box="[977,1049,1014,1039]" name="Brazil" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. It seems to be restricted to coastal environments of the Brazilian Amazon such as mangrove forests and beaches, where it is relatively common. We reared some specimens from a dead crab [
<emphasis box="[623,805,1086,1111]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Ucides cordatus</emphasis>
(Linnaeus)].
</paragraph>
